## Overview

**Meridia** (formerly **Merid-Nunda**) is the Daedric Prince of Light, Life, and Energy. She is unique among the Princes because she is **not originally from Oblivion** — she was once a **Magne-Ge** (spirit of Aetherius) who was banished for consorting with Daedra.

Her hatred of the undead is absolute and fundamentally distinguishes her from the other Princes.

## Origins

### Merid-Nunda
Before becoming "Meridia," she was **Merid-Nunda** — a spirit of light who lived in Aetherius:
- She was one of the Magne-Ge (those who followed Magnus out of Mundus)
- She consorted with Daedric spirits, violating the laws of Aetherius
- She was banished by the other Magne-Ge
- She carved out a domain in Oblivion — the **Colored Rooms**
- She retained her "luminous" nature despite her Daedric status

This origin explains why Meridia:
- Despises the undead (a perversion of life, which she considers sacred)
- Can manipulate light like no other Daedra
- Is uncomfortable among the other Princes
- Has an ambiguous relationship with the Divines

## The Colored Rooms

Her realm, the **Colored Rooms**, is:
- An infinite space of pure, prismatic light
- Crystalline platforms floating in luminosity
- Without shadow, without darkness, without rest
- Inhabited by the **Aurorans** — her golden servants
- Paradoxically oppressive — constant light is a form of torture

## Dawnbreaker

**Dawnbreaker** is her Daedric artifact:
- A golden-bladed sword emitting supernatural light
- Deals fire damage to undead
- Undead slain by it explode in sunlight (area damage)
- In Skyrim, obtained by cleansing the Temple of Kilkreath of necromancers

## The Hatred of the Undead

For Meridia, necromancy is the **supreme sin**:
- She considers life sacred and death natural
- Reanimating a corpse = perverting the life/death cycle
- Vampires are abominations to be destroyed
- Liches represent the ultimate arrogance
- She makes **no distinction** between "benign" and malign necromancy

### Consequences
This stance places her in conflict with:
- **Molag Bal** (creator of vampires)
- **Mannimarco** (the King of Worms, arch-necromancer)
- **Arkay** himself — whose domain she encroaches upon
- Any Conjuration mage who dabbles in necromancy

## Ayleid Connection

Meridia was intensely venerated by the **Ayleids** (Wild Elves of Cyrodiil):
- Several Ayleid cities were dedicated to her
- They weaponized light through her teachings
- The **Aurorans** (Meridia's golden soldiers) have an Ayleid aesthetic
- The fall of the Ayleids greatly reduced her influence on Mundus

## Personality

Meridia is:
- **Authoritarian** — she demands obedience, not devotion
- **Uncompromising** — zero tolerance toward the undead
- **Contemptuous** — she regards mortals as tools
- **Direct** — unlike other Princes, she does not play subtle games
- **Just** (by her own standards) — she genuinely protects the living

Her voice in Skyrim is amplified, resonant, imposing — she speaks to mortals as a superior to a subordinate, not as a tempter.

## Moral Paradox

Meridia illustrates the moral complexity of the Princes:
- She **protects** the living from the undead (objectively "good")
- She uses mortals as disposable **pawns** (objectively "bad")
- Her light is **oppressive**, not liberating
- She is "good" in her goals but "Daedric" in her methods

The Vigilants of Stendarr still treat her as a Daedra to be fought — a theologically consistent position, if practically debatable.
